******
[1] North Carolina
Date: Thu 25 Oct 2007
Source: Burlington Times-News [edited]
<http://www.thetimesnews.com/articles/bat_7052___article.html/rabies_health.html>


A bat captured in Haw River tested positive for rabies Wednesday [24 Oct
2007], making it the county's 6th case this year. A Keck Road resident
might have been exposed to the bat and is under treatment, the Alamance
County Health Department says. The state's Public Health Lab tested the
animal and provided the county with results Wednesday [24 Oct 2007].

"It's important for people to report exposures from bats to the health
department so that the bat can be tested, when an exposure occurs," said
Carl Carroll, environmental health director, in a press release.

The [US] Centers for Disease Control (CDC) generally defines an exposure as
any direct contact with a live bat. Also, if a bat has been found in a room
where people have been sleeping; if an adult finds a bat in the room with a
previously unattended child; or a bat is found in the presence of a
mentally disabled or intoxicated person, you must assume that an exposure
has occurred.

Carroll encouraged residents to take action to prevent the spread of rabies
by vaccinating pets. The health department will hold a USD 5 rabies
vaccination clinic for dogs and cats at their offices at 209 North
Graham-Hopedale Road in Burlington on 3 Nov 2007 from 9 am to 1 pm. "If
people have dogs and cats that are not on their rabies vaccinations, they
cannot afford to wait," Carroll said.

Vaccinations for dogs and cats must be kept current, otherwise if the
animal is exposed to a known or suspected rabid animal, North Carolina Law
requires that the dog or cat be euthanized or quarantined for 6 months at
an approved animal control facility or a veterinarian's office at the
owner's expense.

Humans who have been exposed to rabies can be treated to prevent the
disease from developing; however rabies is almost always fatal once
symptoms develop. Those bitten by an animal should immediately wash the
wound with soap and warm water, seek medical attention and call the local
animal control or health department.

