[2] Minnesota
Date: Fri 26 Oct 2007
Source: Alexandria Echo Press [edited]
<http://www.echopress.com/articles/index.cfm?id=51180Â§ion=news>


A former Alexandria resident's death from a bat bite is triggering safety
warnings around the state. The 46 year old man, from Monticello, died on 20
Oct 2007 after he was infected with rabies in mid-August [2007].

He reportedly was stacking firewood in his cabin porch in north central
Minnesota when he came in contact with a bat. At the time, he didn't
realize he'd been bitten. There was no blood or puncture marks. He felt
only a pinprick on his hand. Not realizing anything was wrong, he didn't
seek any medical care.

About a month later, he started experiencing some unusual symptoms -- a
tingling in his hand -- and soon after that, he lost his ability to talk
and move. By mid-October [2007], he was in a deep coma. By the time
physicians realized the problem could be traced to a rabid bat, it was too
late.

Treatment of rabies must begin before symptoms appear. Once a person
develops symptoms, the illness is almost always fatal, according to state
health officials.

Rabies is rare [in people?] in the United States, with only one to 3 cases
reported each year. This victim is only the 5th person to die of rabies in
Minnesota in the past century. The other 4 cases happened in 1917, 1964,
1975, and 2000. [Rabies may be rare in Minnesota, as this paragraph
implies, but there are other places in the United States where this is not
likely the case. This paragraph does not indicate if rabies is rare in
animals or people. Certainly there are places in the US where rabies in
animals is not rare. - Mod.TG]

"2 deaths in 7 years is too many," noted Ruth Lynfield, state
epidemiologist in a news release issued Tuesday [23 Oct 2007] concerning
the rabies death. "What is most saddening about these deaths is that they
could have been prevented with prompt medical attention following
exposure." The Minnesota Department of Health is working with several
health care facilities in St. Cloud and Rochester where the victim was
given care to evaluate whether any health care workers may have been
exposed to the rabies virus.

The victim's death underscores the importance of seeking prompt medical
attention if you are bitten by or may have been exposed to an animal that
could be infected with rabies, according to state health officials. Bat
exposures pose a special problem because bat bites are difficult to see and
may not be noticed. If you have any physical contact with a bat, the bat
should be captured and tested for rabies and medical advice should be
sought, health officials said.

If a bat is found in a room with an unattended child, a sleeping person or
anyone who can't reliably communicate what happened, the bat should be
captured and tested for rabies. Most recent cases of rabies in humans in
the US have been due to bat bites that were not recognized or reported,
according to the health department. People who may have been exposed to
rabies are given an injection of rabies immune globulin, and 5 doses of
rabies vaccine, given over a one-month period. Treatment is unnecessary if
the suspected animal can be captured, tested, and found to be free of the
virus.

In the case of dogs, cats, or ferrets, treatment can often be avoided if
the animal is held for observation and remains healthy for 10 days
following the bite. [The time an animal is held in quarantine may depend on
if the animal was vaccinated and which state the bite occurred in. There
seem to be subtle differences in rabies laws between the different states.
- Mod.TG] The state public health veterinarian is also reminding people
that they should get their household pets immunized against rabies. Shots
are available for dogs, cats, and ferrets.

