******
[3] Virginia
Date: Thu 25 Oct 2007
Source: NBC12.com [edited]


One local county is dealing with an increase in rabies, and a lack of rain
could part of the problem. So far this year [2007], Hanover County has had
29 confirmed rabies cases. That's more than double from last year [2006].

Two of those cases include a cat and a cow, and authorities I spoke with
say it's rare and scary to see rabies in domestic animals and livestock.
They are not sure exactly what's causing the spike, but they do have a few
theories.

"There are several different reasons that we've talked about and looked
into," said Sgt Caroline Hairfield of Hanover County Animal Control. One of
those reasons is that people are building homes and businesses close to
animal habitats. "Hanover has topped the 100 thousand population mark. We
are encroaching on their territory, we are moving into their homes,"
Hairfield said.

Another possible factor is this year's [2007] lack of rain. Wild animals
are having to come out for water and food. Whatever the reason, the bottom
line is that more wild animals are interacting with domestic animals and
livestock, spreading a fatal and dangerous disease. Any mammal, including
humans, can get rabies, and that's why it's so important to make sure your
animals are vaccinated.

[byline: Sunni Blevins]

